When a differential equation is in the form $\dfrac{dy}{dx}=f(x)g(y)$ we can try to solve it by separation of variables.

For the equation $\dfrac{dy}{dx}=3x^{-2}e^{-y}$, we have:

$\begin{align}
f(x)&=3x^{-2}
\\\\
g(y)&=e^{-y}
\end{align}$

Now we isolate $y$.

$\begin{align}
y^{-1}&=\dfrac{x^3}{3}+C
\\\\
y^{-1}&=\dfrac{x^3+C_2}{3}
\\\\
y&=\dfrac{3}{x^3+C_2}
\end{align}$

Kajal forgot to account for the $C$ term when she took the reciprocal of the right side of the equation.

Now we isolate $y$.

$\begin{align}
\ln|y-3|&=x^2+C_1
\\\\
e^{\ln|y-3|}&=e^{x^2+C_1}
\\\\
|y-3|&=e^{x^2}e^{C_1}
\\\\
y-3&=Ce^{x^2}
\\\\
y&=Ce^{x^2}+3
\end{align}$

When Tess raises $e$ to the power of the left-hand side of the equation, she must raise $e$ to the power of the entire right-hand side of the equation, including the constant.

Now we isolate $y$.

$\begin{align}
\ln|y+2|&=\dfrac{x^2}{2}+C_1
\\\\
e^{\ln|y+2|}&=e^{^{\large\frac{x^2}{2}+C_1}}
\\\\
|y+2|&=e^{^{\large\frac{x^2}{2}}}e^{C_1}
\\\\
y+2&=Ce^{^{\large\frac{x^2}{2}}}
\\\\
y&=Ce^{^{\large\frac{x^2}{2}}}-2
\end{align}$

Lara has correctly isolated $y$.

When a differential equation is in the form $\dfrac{dy}{dx}=f(x)g(y)$ we can try to solve it by separation of variables.

For the equation $\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\dfrac{4}{xe^{y}}$, we have:

$\begin{align}
f(x)&=\dfrac{4}{x}
\\\\
g(y)&=\dfrac{1}{e^y}
\end{align}$
